STEP 1: Check Gradle Installation

Open terminal and run:

gradle -v

 If version shows → OK
 If not → install Gradle first

 STEP 2: Create Project
mkdir gradleworkspace
cd gradleworkspace
 STEP 3: Initialize Gradle Project
gradle init

 Choose options like:

Type → 1 (Application)
Language → Java
Java version → 21 (or your version)
Build script → Groovy
Test framework → JUnit
 STEP 4: Project Structure

After init, you will see:

gradleworkspace/
 ├── build.gradle
 ├── settings.gradle
 ├── src/
 STEP 5: Edit build.gradle

Open file:

vim build.gradle

Add/confirm this:

plugins {
    id 'java'
    id 'application'
}

group = 'com.example'
version = '1.0-SNAPSHOT'

repositories {
    mavenCentral()
}

dependencies {
    testImplementation 'junit:junit:4.13.2'
}

application {
    mainClass = 'org.example.App'
}

task hello {
    doLast {
        println 'Hello, Gradle!'
    }
}

 (This is shown in page 2 image of your PDF)

 STEP 6: (Optional) Edit settings.gradle
vim settings.gradle

 Remove or comment plugin part (as shown in page 3)

 STEP 7: Build Project
gradle build

 What happens:

Compile code
Run tests
Create JAR file
 STEP 8: Run Application
gradle run

 Runs your main Java class

 STEP 9: Run Custom Task
gradle hello

👉 Output:

Hello, Gradle!
